TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bianchi, Milo
AU  - Bobba, Matteo
T1  - Liquidity, Risk, and Occupational Choices
PY  - 2013
Y1  - 2013/04/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rds031
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 80
IS  - 2
SP  - 491
EP  - 511
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We explore which financial constraints matter most in the choice of becoming an entrepreneur. We consider a randomly assigned welfare programme in rural Mexico and show that cash transfers significantly increase entry into entrepreneurship. We then exploit cross-household variation in the timing of these transfers and find that current occupational choices are significantly more responsive to the transfers expected for the future than to those currently received. Guided by a simple occupational choice model, we argue that the programme has promoted entrepreneurship by enhancing willingness to bear risk as opposed to simply relaxing current liquidity constraints.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rds031
ER  - 



